ANU.name: Matthew Doolan
expertise: Manufacturing Processes And Technologies Excl. Textiles
interest: Matthew Doolan has a range of different research interests mainly in the areas of: Manufacturing Processes, Innovation and Technology Adoption, and Recycling and Life Cycle Assessment.
ANU.biography: Matthew Doolan completed his PhD in process control at Ford Australia's Stamping Operations Facility. He has worked for the Mount Stromlo Observatory on the world's largest telescopes, the Gemini telescopes, and as an academic in the School of Engineering at Australian National University. He has led many manufacturing industry research projects cover the gamut from process and dimensional control with Ford Australia, to supply chain management with Toll Auto Logistics and Futuris, to vehicle recycling with the AutoCRC. He also led the highly acclaimed industry technology roadmapping projects, Automotive Australia 2020 and On Track to 2040. Matthew has also be involved in a range of different commerical activities including work with ANU Enterprise and ANU Connect Ventures.

ANDS-Grants.description: This project aims at carrying out new seminal research on developing an advanced welding quality analysing, monitoring, and system controlling for automotive applications. Such system consists of a quality monitoring system with embedded piezoelectric sensors and a powerful inverse solution approach for identifying material properties of welded components. It will greatly benefit Australian automotive industries by improving their efficiency, economic competitiveness and system performance. The outcomes will be: novel Inverse method for identifying parameters of welding structures; an approach for determining optimal weld parameters from material properties; a technique for determining weld quality from inline welding process measurements.
ANDS-Grants.title: Linkage Projects - Grant ID: LP130101001

ANDS-Grants.description: This training centre aims to train a cohort of industry-focused researchers and to develop new lightweighting technologies, which are key to reducing carbon dioxide (CO2 emissions in transportation. In partnership with domestic and international companies and universities, this centre intends to develop new lightweight materials, advanced manufacturing processes, energy storage designs, and rapid non-destructive evaluation techniques. The intended outcome is to accelerate the transformation of Australia's automotive industry—now facing unprecedented structural adjustment—from vehicle production to export of design and engineering services, high-value products, and novel technology solutions.
ANDS-Grants.title: Industrial Transformation Training Centres - Grant ID: IC160100032
